to plantar fasciitis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHeel pain can be inflammatory at any age\u003C/strong\u003E. It can occur in various pathologies including inflammatory conditions such as plantar fasciitis, which is common in adults, and can occur at any age. Inflammatory conditions can also include systemic diseases like rheumatoid arthritis or ankylosing spondylitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExplanation of incorrect options:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHeel pain in young individuals is often due to metabolic causes\u003C/strong\u003E - While metabolic causes can contribute to heel pain, they are not the most common cause in young individuals. Growth-related issues, such as Sever\u0027s disease, are more typical in younger populations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMost heel spurs arise in the plantar fascia\u003C/strong\u003E - Heel spurs are bony growths that are often associated with plantar fasciopathy. They typically develop on the calcaneus (heel bone) but do not arise from the plantar fascia itself.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlantar fasciopathy is a rare degenerative condition\u003C/strong\u003E - Plantar fasciopathy, also known as plantar fasciitis, is a common degenerative condition that affects plantar fascia causing heel pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHeel pain is always due to plantar fasciitis\u003C/strong\u003E - While plantar fasciitis is a common cause of heel pain, other causes can include metabolic, inflammatory and degenerative pathologies. It is vital to consider these differentials in the diagnostic process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Heel pain can have various causes, including metabolic, inflammatory, and degenerative conditions.","Plantar fasciopathy is a common cause of heel pain and is a degenerative condition affecting the plantar fascia.","Heel spurs are often associated with plantar fasciopathy but arise from the calcaneus, not the plantar fascia."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Dandy, D. J., \u0026 Edwards, D. J. (2009). Essential Orthopaedics and Trauma E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","MacGregor R, Byerly DW. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Foot Bones. 2023 May 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491379"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66056"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18382"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66056"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-22T16:41:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-22T16:41:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11100"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80756"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"descr